By: Brian C Kiedrowski<br>
<br>
Undoubtedly, the Columbia disaster gave us all a degree of shock.  Indeed the crash will go down in history of one of space’s greater tragedies.  The heroes who gave their lives to the space program will be remembered forever.  In the wake of this disaster, like all other disasters before it, we must rise from the debris and start anew.  The benefits of going into space are too great and the costs of not are as well.  The preservation of our species depends upon it.  However, in this new day, we must ponder how to continue with space travel.<br>
<br>
Many will suggest the risks are too great.  Indeed, the risks are great.  However, the European settlement of the Americas was full of peril as well.  Many great ships and expeditions were lost, but that did not halt progress toward the dreams of a new frontier.  This frontier represents near infinite possibilities as the solar system is rich in resources and there is no shortage of space to live.  <br>
<br>
The only thing stopping us is our technological limitations.  Perhaps we can learn from the recent disaster and develop better technologies for reaching space.  This issue must be filled with great discussion with every legitimate point of view considered.  The question comes down to whether or not we should continue with the shuttle or look for new ways to reach space.<br>
<br>
The shuttle is a risky proposition with an estimated 1% failure rate.  Perhaps there is a way to circumvent rocket technology.  It may be possible to lift a spacecraft from ground into the upper atmosphere through a device called a Skyhook attached to a space station.  The idea of a Skyhook or a Space Elevator has long been considered but often shelved as a relic of science fiction.  Current materials could never withstand such stresses required.  However, as we learn more about manipulating the atomic crystalline structure of materials, the possibility of a new kind of “launch” system seems more feasible.<br>
<br>
Although there is no guarantee such a technology could even be feasible for space travel, the benefits of research have implications even beyond the space program.  New stronger materials could revolutionize construction ultimately making buildings safer.  Costs and risks of construction could be drastically reduced with the assistance of stronger cables.  And even if a Skyhook is never possible, these new materials could be employed in future space vehicles reducing risk of instabilities and increasing heat resistance.<br>
<br>
Another, and somewhat counterintuitive way, of making space flight safer is the use of nuclear technology.  Images of debris falling over the South following the Columbia crash no doubt come to mind.  Indeed, radioactive debris raining on the United States would be a very bad thing.  <br>
<br>
So how does this help safety?  Nuclear energy release is a million times more energetic than the energy liberated from breaking the chemical bonds used in current fuels.  This equates to a more efficient and contained power supply meaning a space vehicle can carry more weight with it.  Some of this increased weight can be devoted to increasing the safety mechanisms of the vehicle.  Additionally, the nuclear reactor can be contained so that, in the event of a worst-case scenario, none or very little of the radioactive isotopes are released into the atmosphere.<br>
<br>
Beyond launch and re-entry safety, nuclear propulsion creates a much more efficient push in space meaning destinations can be reached faster.  This equates to less radiation exposure for the crew on board, which can be very significant over an extended period of time.  Also, more electrical energy can be generated from the reactor giving the spacecraft greater scientific experimental potential while in space.  This also means more room for error as a small disaster need not totally cripple the craft and maroon the crew in space.  Electrical power is at a premium in space and is nearly as valuable as food and water.<br>
<br>
